description: From Middle English chicke, chike, variation of chiken (“chicken", also "chick”), from Old English ċicen, ċycen (“chicken”). Sense of "young woman" dates to at least 1860 (compare chit (“young, pert woman”)). More at chicken.

entries.meaning: (colloquial, somewhat derogatory) A young, typically attractive, woman or teenage girl.
examples: They're going to have a chick weekend. No guys allowed.
He'll fall for any chick with a nice smile.

The Aldis lamp flashes at the underside of each aircraft. It shows that the gear is down. Diegal is relaxing. This is such low responsibility, easy night duty. All the “chicks” (fighter aircraft) are home to roost except one.

verbs.description: chick (third-person singular simple present chicks, present participle chicking, simple past and past participle chicked)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To sprout, as seed does in the ground; to vegetate.
To compress the lips and then separate them quickly, resulting in a percussive noise.

description: Borrowed from Urdu چق‎ f (ciq), ultimately from Persian چق‎ f (čeq).

entries.meaning: (India, Pakistan) A screen or blind made of finely slit bamboo and twine, hung in doorways or windows.
examples: Then, through a cautiously lifted chick, the old scene stands revealed  […]
